{"author":{"id":"68dfa65ee618df2786e7da658bbfbbcc1f0c757170d9426e314e5f0886bcc55d"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1739179857,"nonce":"Q4K9kEXVXlRLeRUp5KGh06Fv+Tw=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s6dzHAC","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/6717#issuecomment-2647420930"},"message":"Anything that avoids the non-zero exit code would be fine for us. \n\nI guess the easiest option would be to catch the `OSError: [Errno 30] Read-only file system:` exception and print an message to the user (stdout / stderr is both fine). If you like you can also return a non-zero exit code, but it should be a specific number (then the Galaxy datamanager can recognize this and accept the run as successful).\n\nAlternatively add a flag that just disables the writing of the json file. This might be even cleaner.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1739179995,"nonce":"ZgxdDszAhWOjKXlrB2EbSmcYpRA=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s6dzITX","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/6717#issuecomment-2647426263"},"message":"Environment variable is not really necessary as long as `--database_path` covers everything if the file is absent.","files":null}]}